      body: `Every year around June 1st, the India Meteorological Department (IMD) makes a single announcement that affects 1.4 billion people: "The monsoon has arrived in Kerala." It's the most anticipated weather update in the world — because for India, the monsoon isn't just weather. It's the economy, the food supply, and the mood of an entire nation.\n\nIndia's agricultural sector accounts for about 15% of GDP and employs over 40% of the workforce. Unlike developed nations where agriculture relies on irrigation infrastructure, roughly half of India's farmland depends entirely on monsoon rain. A good monsoon means a bumper crop, low food inflation, happy rural economy, and rising stock markets. A poor monsoon means drought, crop failure, farmer distress, and inflation that hits the poorest hardest.\n\nThe monsoon's arrival is dramatic. After months of scorching summer (April-May), when temperatures in central India regularly cross 45 degrees Celsius, suddenly the sky darkens, the wind shifts, and the first raindrops fall. The petrichor — that unique smell of dry earth absorbing rain — is so beloved in India that there's a perfume industry around it (mitti attar, made in Kannauj, UP). Bollywood has immortalized the monsoon in countless rain songs.\n\nBut the monsoon isn't just romantic — it's also catastrophic. Mumbai regularly floods when monsoon rain exceeds the city's drainage capacity. Kerala suffered devastating floods in 2018 and 2019. The same rain that feeds crops also destroys homes. India's relationship with the monsoon is love and fear in equal measure.`
